My first take on $BYND is the chart is a lot like blockchain and then the cannabis hype. Any company can have a solid product/something may be a strong investment, but hype (flash bubbles) can bring stocks down just as fast as they went up. Sometimes I find it disappointing when a potentially solid company (jk I don't look at fundamentals) is subject to such moves; I find that it takes them long to recover if at all following short attacks and/or momentum/FOMO traders taking profit/losses. Just my thoughts, not saying what happened to other names in blockchain/cannabis will happen here, but be aware.

@Tell_It_Right @StockTwits So I guess this is what I'm trying to get at. These parallels have been talked about for awhile, along with inverted yield curve (inversion does not always lead to recession), $TLT picking up, slowing GDP, trade wars, etc. But markets are based and priced on speculation of the future, think about how stocks may react negatively to negative future guidance when the quarter may have had good results. It's my belief that many of these speculations/factors have already been priced in (20% "correction"/mini-bear market 2018). Many don't think about this and just take the "bad news" as is. Things would have to keep getting progressively worse, which is definitely a possibility. But, let's say for example a slow down, it is not always necessarily a bad thing especially after very hot growth periods.
